title: Part 2
content:
Part 2

BY THE TIME we turned five, the number of children had drastically decreased to about fifty.

No one paid attention to it. There was no room to care.

Here, only our abilities were continuously demanded of us.

There was no end.

No, if there was an end, it would be very far and unreachable.

If we ever stopped, we probably wouldn't be able to catch up again.

Did we think this wasn't normal?

I don't think so. This was our everyday life.

One evening, when the number of children had significantly decreased, dinner time arrived.

The meal proceeded with everyone gathered together. During the meal, the instructors would leave, and it was a time when only children were present. However, we had never directly spoken to each other.

The whole time, we had only heard each other's voices when we were talking to the instructors.

Why didn't we talk?

It wasn't forbidden by the instructors.

There was simply no need to initiate conversation, so we didn't.

We knew each other's names through the instructors, and how well we could study or how good our athletic abilities were. Our inner abilities were completely exposed.

There basically weren't any foods we favored or disliked.

Everyone followed the rule of eating whatever was served.

Thus, there was no need to talk about the meal.

There was no sense of us being comrades who learned together.

Our presence, neither helping nor hindering each other, was just, well, no different from the surrounding scenery.

"I don't like it…"

Yuki, the girl who always sat in front of me, muttered softly during the meal.

Talking privately during meals wasn't forbidden, so it wasn't a problem. It was just that no one felt the need to talk.

In the midst of this, the first change occurred.

No one answered, and no one reacted, so she would probably just stop talking, but Yuki didn't.

"Kiyotaka, do you like it?"

She asked me, sitting in front of her, whether I liked carrots.

To answer or not to answer.

To begin with, I had never really thought about whether I liked or disliked carrots.

I only saw them as one of the nutrients humans should consume.

Carrots are primarily a source of beta-carotene.

When consumed, they transform into Vitamin A in the body.

They help prevent cell aging and maintain skin and mucous membrane health. They're extremely important for immunity against viruses—

"Do you like carrots? Or do you not?"

"I don't like them either."

The answer came not from me, who was asked, but from Shiro, who was sitting on my left.

Yuki looked surprised and turned her gaze towards him.

While their conversation captured my attention, I checked the surveillance camera.

Of course, the instructors were monitoring our mealtime daily. They must've been picking up the audio as well. Since there was no particular scolding and no reaction, we must've been allowed to have such conversations.

However, we had never been encouraged to engage in conversation before.

Since there was no apparent benefit to deliberately engaging myself in their conversation, there was no need to respond following the two.

Still… I considered it for a moment.

Whether I liked or disliked carrots.

...the answer was that I didn't dislike it.

After completing my meal, I always found myself a little troubled. I hadn't learned how to kill time.

Sitting and waiting was the easiest and the only option I had.

However, Yuki seemed different; after eating, she would walk around the room alone.

Although I thought walking was just a waste of energy, I silently watched her.

After about three laps around the small room, just as she was passing in front of me…

"Waa…!"

Yuki almost stumbled and fell right before me.

I instinctively reached out and prevented her fall.

"It's strange to trip over nothing,"

I commented, having analyzed the situation, and Yuki looked surprised, her eyes wide.

"Or maybe it's accumulated fatigue? No, it doesn't seem like it."

I couldn't understand why she had tripped.

And it seemed that Yuki didn't understand either.

"Yeah. I'm not tired, but I somehow tripped. It's a bit strange, isn't it?"

She spoke with an expression I had never seen before.

The expression created by the muscles in her face, the orbicularis oculi around her eyes, and the corrugator supercilii near her eyebrows was a first.

It was something I had neither seen from my peers nor the adults teaching us.

The girl herself seemed to have noticed my puzzled look.

"Ah… just now, I…"

She clearly appeared confused and perplexed.

That was to be expected.

She hadn't been taught such things. She hadn't been taught to make that expression.

However, she had the knowledge.

It didn't take long for her to realize that it was a 'smile.'

Something humans have from birth, or perhaps even before, as an instinct.

Perhaps that was why she could manage it without learning.
